    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much protein can your body absorb in one meal?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Your body can absorb virtually unlimited protein in one meal — gut absorption has no meaningful ceiling. What does have a ceiling is how much absorbed protein your muscles can use for muscle protein synthesis (MPS) per sitting. For men over 40, that practical threshold is 30–40g per meal due to anabolic resistance.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is there a protein absorption limit per meal?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">There is no hard absorption limit — your digestive system absorbs essentially all the protein you consume, regardless of amount. The real limit is in muscle protein synthesis utilization, not absorption. Your muscles plateau in their anabolic response at around 30–40g per meal for men over 40, but protein above that threshold is still absorbed and used for other metabolic functions.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much protein can the body absorb at once?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The body can absorb essentially all protein consumed in a single meal — hundreds of grams if eaten. Dr. Stuart Phillips at McMaster University, whose research is the gold standard on this topic, has stated clearly that absorption is not a limiting factor. The limiting factor is muscle protein synthesis, which plateaus at around 40g for older men. Protein above that threshold is absorbed and used elsewhere in the body.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much protein per meal for men over 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Research supports 30–40g of complete protein per meal for men over 40 to reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis. This is higher than the commonly cited 20–25g figure, which was derived from studies on younger men. The higher threshold is a direct result of anabolic resistance — the reduced sensitivity of aging muscle to protein signals. Hitting 30–40g per meal at 3–4 meals daily is the practical target.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What happens to protein your body doesn't use for muscle building?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Protein that exceeds the muscle protein synthesis threshold is not excreted — it's absorbed and redirected to energy production, immune function, enzyme and hormone synthesis, and reducing muscle protein breakdown. From a muscle preservation standpoint, protein above the per-meal MPS threshold contributes progressively less to muscle building per gram consumed — but it is not wasted by the body.</div>
      </div>

